<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Developer-ID (DEVID) entitlements for the embedded LoginItem
  (CLIPulseHelper.app, bundle id yyh.CLI-Pulse.helper). Selected ONLY by
  scripts/build_signed_app.sh when DEVID_BUILD_FLAG=1; the Mac App Store
  archive keeps the sandboxed CLIPulseHelper.entitlements (MAS requires
  every nested executable to be sandboxed — ITMS-90296).

  Why unsandboxed on DEVID: the DEVID app is signed with
  CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO, so Xcode never embeds a provisioning profile.
  A SANDBOXED nested LoginItem that also requests restricted entitlements
  (keychain-access-groups / application-groups) has no profile to authorise
  them, so taskgated/AMFI can reject it on SMAppService.loginItem launch
  (HelperLogin.register, CLIPulseBarApp.swift). Dropping the sandbox
  sidesteps the profile requirement entirely: on an unsandboxed
  Developer-ID binary the app-group + keychain group are honoured via the
  team signature (KHMK6Q3L3K), the same proven config the LaunchAgent
  helper (HelperSwift/cli_pulse_helper.entitlements) already ships. The
  parent app is itself unsandboxed on DEVID, so this keeps the LoginItem
  consistent with it.

  KEPT: application-groups + keychain-access-groups (prompt-free reads of
  the provider apiKey/cookie items the main app writes) + network.client.
  DROPPED: com.apple.security.app-sandbox.
  build_signed_app.sh expands `$(AppIdentifierPrefix)` at sign time.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>com.apple.security.application-groups</key>
	<array>
		<string>group.yyh.CLI-Pulse</string>
	</array>
	<key>keychain-access-groups</key>
	<array>
		<string>$(AppIdentifierPrefix)group.yyh.CLI-Pulse</string>
	</array>
	<key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
	<true/>
</dict>
</plist>
